bout errors, but I want to ensure comprehensive coverage and mention potential issues if the tests aren't running as expected. Let's think through how classpath settings might affect this.\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Analyzing classloader issues**\\n\\nAlright, it looks like there was an issue where the `helperClassesDir` was on the dotc classpath but not accessible by the classloader. Now, the classloader can find `RuntimeMappers`, which is good! I have to make sure that the test classes are actually included in the `java.class.path`. If they’re not found, I can enhance the classpath using the test class’s location. I’m also thinking about potential compile errors and how macro retrieval might work here, especially concerning the classloader. Let's work through this carefully!\"}]}"}, {"type": "text", "text": "Fixed the runtime test failure by removing the temp-compiled Scala fixture object.\n\nThe failure happened because `QuoteScope.retrieveRuntimeModule` uses `Class.forName(sym.fullName + \"$\")`, which looks through the test JVM’s class loader, not just the Dotty compiler classpath. The temp-compiled `RuntimeMappers$` was visible to Dotty for typechecking, but not to `Class.forName`.\n\nChanges made in:\n\n`tests/src/com.github.plokhotnyuk.jsoniter-scala/jsoniter-scala-macros_3/2.33.3/src/test/scala/com_github_plokhotnyuk_jsoniter_scala/jsoniter_scala_macros_3/CompileTimeEvalInnerQuoteScopeTest.scala`\n\n- Moved the mapper fixture into the test Scala source itself as top-level test fixtures:\n  - `RuntimeMappersForQuoteScopeTest`\n  - `RuntimeMapperHolderForQuoteScopeTest`\n- The runtime-compiled macro source now imports those fixtures from the already-loaded test classpath.\n- Removed the temp helper source compilation path that caused `Class.forName` to fail.\n\nI did not run the tests locally.", "textSignature": "{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_0de9e442508f38ed016a1155da9e208196948bae727317f6f3\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}], "api": "openai-responses"